<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Soviets Catching Up on Debt Payments: The Soviet Union is repaying overdue debt 
to foreign firms, but not as fast as it would like, one of the country's top 
bankers said in an interview published over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
The Communist Party daily Pravda quoted Yuri Moskovsky, head of the Bank for 
Foreign Economic Affairs, as saying that more than $1.75 billion has been 
repaid the past two months. Late payments by Soviet foreign trade 
organizations, which were until recently prompt payers, have worried Western 
creditors this year. But bankers say matters improved after Moscow borrowed 
$3.2 billion from West Germany in June. 
</P>
</TEXT>
