<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION; 
</P>
<P>
UAW MEMBERS APPROVE GM PACT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
DETROIT 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The United Auto Workers said today that its members approved a new three-year 
contract with General Motors by an overwhelming margin, setting the stage for 
talks with the two other U.S. auto makers. 
</P>
<P>
The UAW said the pact, which provides for wage increases, improved pension 
benefits and a multibillion-dollar job and income security fund, was approved 
by 80% of those voting. It covers about 3,000 active and laid-off workers. 
</P>
<P>
According to the union, production and maintenance workers approved the pact 
63,963 to 15,787. Among skilled workers, 22,069 voted for the pact and 5,674 
voted against it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
