<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD; 
</P>
<P>
ALLIES RENOUNCE GERMAN RIGHTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Service Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The four victorious powers of World War II today suspended all their rights in 
Germany including Berlin, clearing the way for Germany to become fully 
sovereign when it unites Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
Ministers of the four powers -- the United States, the Soviet Union, Britain 
and France -- joined the two Germanys in signing an agreement in New York 
suspending their rights from the moment unification comes into force Oct. 3. 
</P>
<P>
Formal termination of rights will take effect when a treaty signed last month 
is ratified by the parliaments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
