<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
SOVIET SHELVES NEED $12 BILLION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PARIS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Soviet Union will need at least $12 billion in aid to fill empty store 
shelves with imports and get a free market started, President Mikhail S. 
Gorbachev's personal economic adviser said in an interview published today. 
</P>
<P>
"You cannot begin the transition to the market (economy) with empty shops. . . 
. To start up the market, we need a massive injection of all sorts of consumer 
goods," Nikolai Petrakov told the French business daily Tribune de l'Expansion. 
</P>
<P>
He said that foreign companies, banks and governments have already offered such 
credits, and he estimated that "a minimum $10 billion to $12 billion" will be 
needed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
